{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608231"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:31:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:31:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15994"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15994"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8685"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7113"},{"type":"tags","id":"8662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8663"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20789"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the neural tube forms three primary vesicles: the prosencephalon (forebrain), mesencephalon (midbrain), and rhombencephalon (hindbrain). The prosencephalon undergoes further subdivision and development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the adult structures that develop from the embryonic forebrain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebellum and pons","Midbrain and superior colliculi","Medulla oblongata and fourth ventricle","Cerebral hemispheres and diencephalon","Spinal cord and central canal"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe embryonic forebrain (prosencephalon) develops into two major divisions: the telencephalon and diencephalon. The telencephalon gives rise to the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral hemispheres\u003C/strong\u003E including the cerebral cortex, white matter, basal ganglia, and limbic structures. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ediencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E develops into the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus, and subthalamus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum and pons\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the metencephalon portion of the hindbrain. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emidbrain and superior colliculi\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the mesencephalon. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emedulla oblongata and fourth ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the myelencephalon portion of the hindbrain. The \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord and central canal\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the caudal portion of the neural tube.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The embryonic forebrain (prosencephalon) develops into the telencephalon and diencephalon.","The telencephalon forms the cerebral hemispheres, basal ganglia, and limbic structures.","The diencephalon develops into the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus, and subthalamus."],"references":["Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Jernigan TL, Stiles J. Construction of the human forebrain. Wiley Interdiscip Rev Cogn Sci. 2017 Jan;8(1-2):10.1002/wcs.1409. doi: 10.1002/wcs.1409. Epub 2016 Dec 1. PMID: 27906520; PMCID: PMC5182182."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15994"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T11:57:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T11:57:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8685"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving informati